										<content:encoded><!--[CDATA[
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-style-center-align-caption"--><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-Brown-is-writing-book-about-double-lung-transplant-16-x-9-1024x576.jpg" alt="Barbara Brown, double lung transplant patient" class="wp-image-408398" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-Brown-is-writing-book-about-double-lung-transplant-16-x-9-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-Brown-is-writing-book-about-double-lung-transplant-16-x-9-300x169.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-Brown-is-writing-book-about-double-lung-transplant-16-x-9-768x432.jpg 768w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-Brown-is-writing-book-about-double-lung-transplant-16-x-9-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-Brown-is-writing-book-about-double-lung-transplant-16-x-9.jpg 1824w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Barbara Brown is writing a book about her double-lung transplant journey</figcaption>



<p>Barbara Brown was working in New York City when the Sept. 11 attacks occurred. Exposure to toxins led to years of struggling to breathe and searching for answers.</p>



<p>Barbara's journey led her to <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mayo Clinic</a> and, ultimately, a life-changing double-lung transplant. With renewed strength, Barbara shares what drives her to educate others about <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/departments-centers/transplant-center/sections/expertise-ranking/orc-20203899?customer_id=173-378-9621&amp;mc_id=google&amp;campaign=13708841197&amp;geo=9011567&amp;kw=lung%20and%20heart%20transplant%20mayo%20clinic&amp;ad=728805550217&amp;network=g&amp;sitetarget=&amp;adgroup=123779045426&amp;extension=&amp;target=kwd-1285271328158&amp;matchtype=p&amp;device=c&amp;account=1733789621&amp;invsrc=transplant&amp;placementsite=enterprise&amp;gad_source=1&amp;gad_campaignid=13708841197&amp;gbraid=0AAAAAD8Qu29D9AlFbLExyWIlceN9AOEXJ&amp;gclid=CjwKCAiAlfvIBhA6EiwAcErpyTS0ATGHLGjlFF0A3JUdKM_FcBhGJjnV96xmKuXTxNlAg29RoP0iEBoCt9cQAvD_BwE" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">transplants</a>.</p>



<p><strong><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=00oS3B90JMk" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Watch: Double-lung transplant inspires mom to educate and support others</a></strong></p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<div class="fluidEmbed"><iframe loading="lazy" id="videoidhttpsyoutube00oS3B90JMk" title="Double-lung transplant inspires mom to educate and support others" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/00oS3B90JMk?feature=oembed&amp;enablejsapi=1" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen=""></iframe></div>
</div></figure>



<p><strong>Journalists: Broadcast-quality video pkg (2:14) is in the downloads&nbsp;at the end of the post. Please courtesy: "Mayo Clinic News Network." Read the&nbsp;<a href="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Script_Double-lung-transplant-inspires-mom-to-educate-and-support-others.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">script</a>.</strong></p>



<p>"I was meeting my girlfriends for breakfast," Barbara says. "She actually worked in the World Trade Center. When the actual plane hit the tower, I wasn't right up on the towers, but I was where you could see it."</p>



<p>What followed that day would change Barbara's health and life forever.</p>



<p>"All of this stuff that was in your lungs," Barbara recalls.</p>



<p>Over time, Brown started to notice changes in her health. Then, a pivotal moment in 2006 while being a mom to an active 2-year-old girl.</p>



<p>"(My daughter) jumped up in my arms, and I kind of fell backward. And I fell down, and I couldn't hold her," Barbara says. "That was the first big thing with my lungs."</p>



<p>Barbara was diagnosed with <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/interstitial-lung-disease/symptoms-causes/syc-20353108" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">interstitial lung disease</a>, where inflammation and scarring make it difficult to breathe. Doctors explained that someday she would need a lung transplant.</p>



<p>"I looked at this little girl that I had, and I said, 'You know, if I'm going to fight, I'm going to fight for her, you know,'" Barbara says. "And so that's what I chose to do."</p>



<p>Barbara spent much of the next decade searching for a transplant program that would be the right fit. She traveled across the country speaking with care teams and taking evaluations — all while her lungs grew weaker. Then, Mayo Clinic entered her life.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image is-style-center-align-caption">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Dr.-Narula-and-Barbara-Brown-talking-1024x576.jpg" alt="Dr. Tagathat Narula meets with Barbara Brown in Oct. 2025, eight and a half years after her transplant." class="wp-image-408250" style="width:793px;height:auto" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Dr.-Narula-and-Barbara-Brown-talking-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Dr.-Narula-and-Barbara-Brown-talking-300x169.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Dr.-Narula-and-Barbara-Brown-talking-768x432.jpg 768w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Dr.-Narula-and-Barbara-Brown-talking-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Dr.-Narula-and-Barbara-Brown-talking.jpg 1920w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dr. Tagathat Narula meets with Barbara Brown in Oct. 2025, eight and a half years after her transplant.</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<p>"Barbara came through our doors, referred to us from an outside provider, with a disease that was fairly advanced," <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/biographies/narula-tathagat-m-b-b-s-m-d/bio-20305908" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dr. Tathagat Narula</a>, a Mayo Clinic <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/departments-centers/transplant-center/home/orc-20203891" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">transplant</a> pulmonologist, says. "She was on a lot of oxygen, very, very sick."</p>



<p>After qualifying for a double-lung transplant and spending time on the waiting list, Barbara got the call in April 2017.</p>



<p>"It's the scariest thing in the world because now you're looking at everybody and you're like, 'This is it!'" Barbara says. "'This is really it!'"</p>



<p>Recovery would be long, but after <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/departments-centers/physical-medicine-rehabilitation-mayo-clinic/sections/overview/ovc-20467039" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">physical therapy</a> to regain her strength, Barbara was breathing without assistance and ready to pick up where her life had paused. The journey has also inspired her to share her story and dispel misconceptions about transplant.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-with-care-team-in-2017-1024x576.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-408271" style="width:596px;height:auto" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-with-care-team-in-2017-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-with-care-team-in-2017-300x169.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-with-care-team-in-2017-768x432.jpg 768w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-with-care-team-in-2017-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2025/11/Barbara-with-care-team-in-2017.jpg 1920w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Barbara Brown with her Mayo Clinic care team in 2017 upon completing physical rehabilitation.</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<p>"I decided that I was going to really write about my experience," Barbara says. "If I can do something to get the information out there, and I said, 'I'm going to maybe attempt at it this way.'"</p>



<p>"In Barbara's case, she has had this opportunity to see her daughter grow up, go to college," Dr. Narula says. " Barbara is writing a book to share her journey, to share her story with the wider audience. What more can you ask for?"</p>



<p>Eight and a half years after transplant, she's happy and excited for her next chapter.</p>



<p>"Do I look like someone who's been through a double-lung transplant? No, but what does someone look like? If someone says I look like a happy person, then that's what I would prefer looking like," Barbara says.</p>



